itish power. Written from a theoretically-informed perspective, grounded in rich archival sources, oral testimonies and a revisionist reading of the literature on counter-insurgency and counter-terrorism, this is the definitive account of the politics of Britain’s small wars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil-military relationszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aLow-intensity conflicts (Military science)zGreat BritainxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Military / Wars & Conflicts (Other).2bisacsh  a9/11.  aBritain.  aCivil-military relations.  aCold War.  aCounter-insurgency.  aCounter-terrorism.  aDecolonisation.  aMilitary intervention.  aSmall wars.  aStrategy.1 aEdwards, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526129956423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526129956/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles